```
go version go1.26-devel_e7c0b74a97 Tue Jan 6 20:29:01 2026 +0100 linux/amd64
```
I don't know what the name is for this pattern so I've made one up, but basically the assembly for this function looks awful:
```go
func ConstantTimeCompare(x, y []byte) int {
	if len(x) != len(y) { panic("...") }

	var v byte

	for ; len(x) > 0; x, y = x[1:], y[1:] {
		a := y[0]
		b := x[0]

		v |= a ^ b
	}

	return constanttime.Eq(v, 0)
}
```
- after early loop rotation #77089 we could move `s[1:]` operations into `if len(x) > 0 { /* here */; goto loop }` second loop check, this would allow us to remove the slice mask
- we keep track of the length of both slices, even tho it is identical

comment.body:
@ruhil6789 were you able to reproduce the issue?

At a high level, the description of the fix you sent doesn't make much sense to me. Perhaps I'm missing something and there's an even worse bug at play here, but AFAICT, `nextMarkBitArenaEpoch` cannot execute concurrently with `newMarkBits` since it only executes during a stop-the-world. Did you see evidence of such a race in any kind of reproducer?

Assuming we haven't seen more of these, I'm inclined to blame the Darwin machines being flaky with file corruption again, though that's getting more and more unsatisfying.

@junpuf Thanks for your work! I think it is in good shape, with some minor comments:

* There should be some checks in case `FINAL_BASE_IMAGE` is overridden to use a newer version. For example, only do the debianization if `"$(lsb_release -c -s)" == "jammy"`?
* #30443 could be merged first. Although your changes are orthogonal, there might be potential merge conflicts.

issue.body:
Recently, I started working on https://github.com/yocto/pkcs11-module-kmip-go, because I couldn't find any PKCS#11 module that did this. I chose Go, because OVH had made KMIP library for it. I also wanted to prevent C/C++ as much as possible. When having NGINX in some development mode, it went well and I saw more and more things get working slowly until the point I really could do messaging over TLS 1.2.

However, NGINX in development mode (`master_process off;`) isn't good for production environments, so I tested it too with `master_process on;` (or just remove the setting entirely). NGINX still loaded my module when starting up or when reloading, but the problems began when SSL/TLS requests started coming in. I saw in the logs that the responsible worker caused `C_Finalize` being called. With some more debugging and logging, I found out that my module started to hang on the following line: https://github.com/yocto/pkcs11-module-kmip-go/blob/049b374f6a24e23266ec7b83a8cde6140489a8be/main.go#L269, which is a function of https://github.com/ovh/kmip-go. I didn't dig deeper in that library, so I don't know what exact operation in there causes the problem. When retrying the same SSL/TLS request, my second worker also started to hang, making my whole webserver unavailable.

In production environments, NGINX makes use of workers and these workers are created using forking. I think the problem has something to do with that. I have read some things about Go becoming unstable after forking, but `fmt.Printf` and many other functions still worked, so it isn't totally broken.

Now, I want to know exactly what causes the thing to hang. I have choosen Go over C/C++ and others, because I saw a Go library for KMIP and some other reasons. Rewriting this in C/C++, Zig, Rust or some other thing would be far much more work. I hope to continue working in Go with this project.

I saw people suggesting that Go is multithreaded and forking causes threads to disappear, including the `netpoller`. However, in `htop` I never saw any other threads than the NGINX master and NGINX worker. Are there any hidden threads? Or are those blue threads (see image) nameless Go threads?
<img width="1275" height="268" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/33c82df1-32dd-4fe5-8783-f76a4cc5deae" />

Also, I made my own code to test how forking works:

```go
package main

/*
#include <unistd.h>
pid_t doFork(){
    return fork();
}
*/
import "C"
import "fmt"
import "net/http"

var isChild bool

func main() {
        doBefore()

        rv := C.doFork()

        if rv == -1 {
                fmt.Println("FORK ERROR")
                return
        }

        if rv == 0 {
                fmt.Println("WELCOME CHILD")
                isChild = true
        } else {
                fmt.Println("WELCOME BACK PARENT")
        }

        doAfter()
}

func doBefore() {
        fmt.Println("BEFORE")

        resp, err := http.Get("http://ipecho.net/plain")
        if err != nil {
                fmt.Println(err)
        } else {
                fmt.Println(resp)
        }
}

func doAfter() {
        fmt.Println("AFTER")

        resp, err := http.Get("http://ipecho.net/plain")
        if err != nil {
                if isChild {
                        fmt.Print("[C] ")
                } else {
                        fmt.Print("[P] ")
                }
                fmt.Println(err)
        } else {
                if isChild {
                        fmt.Print("[C] ")
                } else {
                        fmt.Print("[P] ")
                }
                fmt.Println(resp)
        }
}
```
Running thise code produced the following logs:
```
BEFORE
&{200 OK 200 HTTP/1.1 1 1 map[Access-Control-Allow-Origin:[*] Content-Length:[14] Content-Type:[text/plain; charset=utf-8] Date:[Sat, 31 Jan 2026 16:40:26 GMT] Via:[1.1 google]] 0xc0000a6400 14 [] false false map[] 0xc0000dc000 <nil>}
WELCOME BACK PARENT
AFTER
WELCOME CHILD
AFTER
[C] &{200 OK 200 HTTP/1.1 1 1 map[Access-Control-Allow-Origin:[*] Content-Length:[14] Content-Type:[text/plain; charset=utf-8] Date:[Sat, 31 Jan 2026 16:40:27 GMT] Via:[1.1 google]] 0xc0000a65c0 14 [] false false map[] 0xc0000dc140 <nil>}
[P] &{200 OK 200 HTTP/1.1 1 1 map[Access-Control-Allow-Origin:[*] Content-Length:[14] Content-Type:[text/plain; charset=utf-8] Date:[Sat, 31 Jan 2026 16:40:32 GMT] Via:[1.1 google]] 0xc000066100 14 [] false false map[] 0xc0000dc140 <nil>}
```
It just works, so networking seems not to be broken either, even when threads have disappeared.

Because my client keeps alive the TCP connection, maybe the problem could be that. However, in that case I would expect that creating a new client and using that one would fix the problem, but that seemed not to be the case.

