issue.body:
Currently, rust-analyzer (intelligently) does not show a named argument hint when passing an argument with the same name as the parameter (e.g. passing in a variable called `bar` to a function `fn foo(bar: ())` does not cause the UI to display `foo(bar: bar)`, it just shows `foo(bar)`).

I propose extending the same to type hints on variable assignment when assigning a structured type directly, e.g.

```rust
let upload = Upload {
...
};
```

should display without any type hints, instead of the current behavior:

<img width="430" height="116" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/5e06c8bd-c721-40cd-bd37-1bf9a4cf1dd1" />

For this specific proposal, I am not requesting for the assignment/binding type hints to be hidden in cases such as this highly related one, where `Upload::new()` returns `Self` (though I think it might merit future consideration):

```rust
let upload = Upload::new(...)
```

or this lesser case where `Upload::foo()` also returns `Self`:

```rust
let upload = Upload::foo() 
```

or this case where God only knows what the ultimate return type would be:

```rust
let upload = Upload {
...
}.foo();
```

_but_ for the specific case covered by this proposal, I would imagine that the type hint would also be elided even in this case:

```rust
let not_upload = Upload {
...
};
```

i.e. even if the binding name isn't the same as the type being assigned.

